    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4317104090" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4317104090" />
    <a title="Lori Keeton" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17557841-lori-keeton"><img alt="Lori Keeton" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1371329305p2/17557841.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4317104090?book_show_action=true">Feb 04, 2022</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lori Keeton" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lori Keeton" href="/user/show/17557841-lori-keeton">Lori Keeton</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140185232" href="/book/show/117834.The_Razor_s_Edge">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17557841-lori-keeton?shelf=literary-fiction">literary-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17557841-lori-keeton?shelf=2022-reads">2022-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17557841-lori-keeton?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17557841-lori-keeton?shelf=philosophy">philosophy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17557841-lori-keeton?shelf=world-war-1">world-war-1</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17557841-lori-keeton?shelf=religion">religion</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4317104090" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2591633472370094034">Thinking about what to say about <b>The Razor’s Edge</b> isn’t an easy task. I don’t really know how to express this book’s message in a well-thought out review as so many already have. This is a book for thinkers and maybe I’m not quite there yet on that aspect. However, I absolutely loved Maugham’s writing style because it was just so easy and flawless. Maugham inserts himself into the narrative which seems to work quite well as being the story teller and conduit of his message and also a character i</span>
  <span id="freeText2591633472370094034" style="display:none">Thinking about what to say about <b>The Razor’s Edge</b> isn’t an easy task. I don’t really know how to express this book’s message in a well-thought out review as so many already have. This is a book for thinkers and maybe I’m not quite there yet on that aspect. However, I absolutely loved Maugham’s writing style because it was just so easy and flawless. Maugham inserts himself into the narrative which seems to work quite well as being the story teller and conduit of his message and also a character in the narrative. He is the writer of Larry Darrell’s story as he interacts with and closely befriends him and his friends. Larry’s story is told through the lens of his friends who have recognized a drastic change in his personality since returning from WW1 where he served as a fighter pilot. Larry is a much more subdued and introspective man now that he has witnessed death. Living a “normal” lifestyle is futile to him and he seems to be grappling with what life is really about, what his life should be about. His friends and his fiancee think he should be making lots of money and working his way up the corporate ladder, moving on with his life and finding meaning through his work and his relationships. But this lifestyle of conforming to the expectations of society will not suit Larry. This is not his definition of happiness. He decides that in order to find what he’s looking for, he wants to “loaf” - his word for reading and gaining knowledge and immersing himself with experiences that will aid in his spiritual journey.<br /><br />This is not a new concept - so many people in the world are searching for meaning in life, searching for God. What is one’s purpose and what is truly important to accomplish? Will one have a fulfilling, meaningful, happy and satisfied life? What does this mean to each one of us? Larry’s determined search and the choices he makes are fulfilling for him and we see through the other characters who make much different choices toward happiness that every person’s view of satisfaction in life is different. Some find happiness in family life and others through work and stability in a lofty bank account or still yet from surrounding themselves with the most expensive things and highest social class. Some won’t fit any sort of mold which society deems as meaningful and those are like Larry - seeking truth through knowledge, philosophies and religion. What this novel shows is that fulfillment in life is an individualistic endeavor. Everyone seeks what they find meaningful for them. It’s a personal choice which makes life worth living for each one of us. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="2591633472370094034" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

